A-Eng. HB 4044
1 (c) Perform other duties assigned by the Director of Human Services or required by law
2 or rule.
3 (5) The office may enter into agreements and acquire services, materials, supplies or
4 equipment necessary to perform its duties before, during and after a disruption.
5 (6) The office may adopt rules necessary to implement and administer this section.
6 SECTION 2. ORS 401.025 is amended to read:
7 401.025. As used in this chapter:
8 (1) “Emergency” means a human created or natural event or circumstance that causes or
9 threatens widespread loss of life, injury to person or property, human suffering or financial loss,
10 including but not limited to:
11 (a) Fire, wildfire, explosion, flood, severe weather, landslides or mud slides, drought, earthquake,
12 volcanic activity, tsunamis or other oceanic phenomena, spills or releases of oil or hazardous mate-
13 rial as defined in ORS 466.605, contamination, utility or transportation emergencies, disease, blight,
14 infestation, civil disturbance, riot, sabotage, acts of terrorism and war; and
15 (b) A rapid influx of individuals from outside this state, a rapid migration of individuals from
16 one part of this state to another or a rapid displacement of individuals if the influx, migration or
17 displacement results from the type of event or circumstance described in paragraph (a) of this sub-
18 section.
19 (2) “Emergency service agency” means an organization within a local government that performs
20 essential services for the public’s benefit before, during or after an emergency, such as law
21 enforcement, fire control, health, medical and sanitation services, human services, public works
22 and engineering, public information and communications.
23 (3) “Emergency services” means activities engaged in by state and local government agencies
24 to prepare for an emergency and to prevent, minimize, respond to or recover from an emergency,
25 including but not limited to coordination, preparedness planning, training, interagency liaison, fire
26 fighting, oil or hazardous material spill or release cleanup as defined in ORS 466.605, law enforce-
27 ment, medical, health and sanitation services, human services, engineering and public works,
28 search and rescue activities, warning and public information, damage assessment, administration and
29 fiscal management, and those measures defined as “civil defense” in 50 U.S.C. app. 2252.
30 (4) “Local government” has the meaning given that term in ORS 174.116.
31 (5) “Major disaster” means any event defined as a “major disaster” under 42 U.S.C. 5122(2).
32 SECTION 3. ORS 401.534 is amended to read:
33 401.534. (1) The Oregon Disaster Response Fund is established in the State Treasury, separate
34 and distinct from the General Fund. Interest earned by the Oregon Disaster Response Fund
35 must be credited to the fund. Moneys received from federal grants for disaster response efforts
36 shall be deposited into the Oregon Disaster Response Fund. Moneys in the fund are continuously
37 appropriated to the Oregon Department of Emergency Management to be used to:
38 (a) Help state agencies and local government units with immediate disaster response and re-
39 covery efforts related to federally declared disasters in this state; and
40 (b) Implement long-term hazard mitigation measures after a federally declared disaster in this
41 state during the period of immediate recovery from the disaster.
42 (2) The Oregon Disaster Response Fund may receive gifts, grants, bequests, endowments and
43 donations from public and private sources for purposes related to the fund.
44 (3) The department shall adopt rules for the disbursement of moneys from the Oregon Disaster
45 Response Fund.
[2]

A-Eng. HB 4044
1 (4) If there are expenditures from the Oregon Disaster Response Fund, the Director of the
2 Oregon Department of Emergency Management shall report to the Emergency Board, or to the
3 Legislative Assembly if it is in session, on:
4 (a) The nature and severity of the disaster;
5 (b) The actual and projected deposits into the fund;
6 (c) The sources of actual and projected expenditures from the fund;
7 (d) The nature of in-kind donations received; and
8 (e) The rationale for expenditures and allocation of payments to state agencies and local gov-
9 ernment units.
10 (5) Following the final expenditure for a particular disaster, the director shall issue a final re-
11 port to the Emergency Board, or to the Legislative Assembly if it is in session. The report must
12 include an aggregate description of the factors described in subsection (4) of this section.
13 SECTION 4. Sections 5 to 8 of this 2026 Act are added to and made a part of ORS chapter
14 401.
15 SECTION 5. (1) The Oregon Department of Emergency Management shall establish and
16 administer a state infrastructure emergency recovery grant program, to be known as the
17 Oregon Public Assistance Grant Program, to issue grants to qualified recipients, subject to
18 available funding.
19 (2) Grants under the program must be used to pay for work performed before, during or
20 after an emergency to protect public health, safety or property, including, without limitation,
21 debris removal and work to protect or restore public services or public infrastructure.
22 (3) The Governor may activate the program if:
23 (a) The Governor determines that an emergency has occurred or is imminent and finds
24 that assistance from the state is warranted; and
25 (b) The department recommends that the program be activated.
26 (4) The Governor shall inactivate the program when the Governor finds that assistance
27 from the state is no longer warranted.
28 (5) While the program is active, the department may issue grants to qualified recipients
29 pursuant to requests from counties or tribal entities. A request on behalf of a city may be
30 made by the county in which a geographic majority of the city lies. Requests must be in
31 writing and must include the following information:
32 (a) Confirmation that the requester has taken appropriate action under the local emer-
33 gency plan;
34 (b) An estimate of the amount and severity of damages and losses and a description of
35 the impact of the emergency on the public and private sectors;
36 (c) A description of the nature and amount of local resources which have been or will
37 be committed to alleviate the results of the emergency;
38 (d) A preliminary estimate of the types and amount of supplementary state emergency
39 assistance needed; and
40 (e) A certification by the requester that the obligations and expenditures for the current
41 emergency will comply with all applicable cost sharing requirements agreed on between the
42 department and the requester.
43 (6) The department may adopt rules to administer and implement the provisions of this
44 section, including rules governing eligibility requirements, the form and manner of requests
45 and evaluation of requests by the department.
[3]

A-Eng. HB 4044
1 (7) As used in this section, “qualified recipient” means:
2 (a) A state agency;
3 (b) A local government;
4 (c) A federally recognized Indian tribe in Oregon;
5 (d) A school district or education service district; and
6 (e) A nonprofit organization that provides critical services or essential social services,
7 such as a hospital, long term care facility, school, community center, food assistance pro-
8 gram or shelter.
9 SECTION 6. The Oregon Public Assistance Grant Program Account is established in the
10 State Treasury, separate and distinct from the General Fund. Interest earned by the account
11 must be credited to the account. The account consists of moneys appropriated, allocated,
12 deposited or transferred to the account by the Legislative Assembly or otherwise and inter-
13 est earned on moneys in the account. The moneys in the account are continuously appro-
14 priated to the Oregon Department of Emergency Management to carry out the Oregon Public
15 Assistance Grant Program described in section 5 of this 2026 Act. The department shall en-
16 sure that no more than 10 percent of the moneys in the account are used to pay costs of
17 coordination and distribution of assistance under the program.
18 SECTION 7. (1) The Department of Human Services shall establish and administer a
19 program, to be known as the Oregon Individual Assistance Program, to provide assistance
20 to address critical emergency-related needs of qualified individuals, subject to available
21 funding.
22 (2) The Governor may activate the program if:
23 (a) The Oregon Department of Emergency Management recommends that the program
24 be activated, the Governor determines that an emergency has occurred or is imminent and
25 the Governor finds that assistance from the state is warranted; or
26 (b) The Governor has declared an emergency under ORS 401.165.
27 (3) The Governor shall inactivate the program when the Governor finds that assistance
28 from the state is no longer warranted.
29 (4) While the program is active, the Department of Human Services may provide assist-
30 ance pursuant to requests from counties or tribal entities. A request on behalf of a city may
31 be made by the county in which a geographic majority of the city lies. Requests must be in
32 writing and must include the following information:
33 (a) Confirmation that the requester has taken appropriate action under the local emer-
34 gency plan;
35 (b) An estimate of the amount and severity of damages and losses and a description of
36 the impact of the emergency on individuals and households;
37 (c) A description of the nature and amount of local resources which have been or will
38 be committed to alleviate the results of the emergency; and
39 (d) A preliminary estimate of the types and amount of supplementary state emergency
40 assistance needed.
41 (5) Assistance under the program may consist of:
42 (a) The provision of services to qualified individuals to address critical emergency-related
43 needs, which may include, without limitation:
44 (A) Temporary rental assistance;
45 (B) Repair or replacement of owner-occupied homes that serve as a primary residence,
[4]

A-Eng. HB 4044
1 including repair or replacement of privately owned access routes;
2 (C) Assistance with immediate needs;
3 (D) Assistance with essential personal property needs that are not covered by insurance;
4 (E) Assistance with other serious needs that are not covered by insurance; and
5 (F) Other critical emergency recovery services as approved by the Oregon Department
6 of Emergency Management; and
7 (b) Agreements with local governments, tribal entities, disaster recovery organizations
8 or other public or private entities for the delivery of services described in paragraph (a) of
9 this subsection, including payments for staffing or other administrative needs.
10 (6) Assistance to qualified individuals may be in the form of direct financial assistance
11 or payments to another entity on behalf of qualified individuals.
12 (7) The Department of Human Services, in consultation with the Oregon Department of
13 Emergency Management, shall adopt rules to administer and implement the provisions of
14 this section.
15 (8) As used in this section:
16 (a) “Immediate need” means:
17 (A) A life-saving or life-sustaining item or activity that is essential to prevent, mitigate
18 or overcome an adverse condition caused by an emergency; and
19 (B) Other equipment that is essential for daily household needs.
20 (b) “Qualified individual” means:
21 (A) An individual who is displaced by an emergency from the individual’s primary resi-
22 dence;
23 (B) An individual whose primary residence is rendered uninhabitable by an emergency;
24 or
25 (C) An individual with a disability whose primary residence is rendered inaccessible or
26 uninhabitable to the individual as a result of damage caused by an emergency.
27 SECTION 8. (1) The Oregon Individual Assistance Program Account is established in the
28 State Treasury, separate and distinct from the General Fund. Interest earned by the account
29 must be credited to the account. The account consists of moneys appropriated, allocated,
30 deposited or transferred to the account by the Legislative Assembly or otherwise and inter-
31 est earned on moneys in the account. The moneys in the account are continuously appro-
32 priated to the Oregon Department of Emergency Management.
33 (2) The department may make moneys in the account available to the Department of
34 Human Services to carry out the Oregon Individual Assistance Program described in section
35 7 of this 2026 Act. Moneys that are made available from the account to the Department of
36 Human Services that are not expended for the Oregon Individual Assistance Program must
37 be redeposited in the account.
38 SECTION 9. The Oregon Department of Emergency Management and the Department of
39 Human Services shall establish an agreement and protocols for sharing data related to the
40 Oregon Public Assistance Grant Program and the Oregon Individual Assistance Program
41 established under sections 5 and 7 of this 2026 Act.
42 SECTION 10. In addition to and not in lieu of any other appropriation, there is appro-
43 priated to the Oregon Department of Emergency Management, for the biennium ending June
44 30, 2027, out of the General Fund, the amount of $500,000, to carry out the provisions of
45 section 7 of this 2026 Act.
